      "text": "The views of the two also differ with regard to the idea of the individual, or individuality. With the progressive functionalization of people in the modern working society and the resulting loss of subjectivity, Arendt simultaneously sees individuality as isolation and thus as a problem. She decisively criticizes this \"peculiar individualization\". For Adorno, the decisive problem is not individualization, but the disintegration and transformation of individuality in modern society from a residuum of potential freedom to \"indifference to the individual\": \"Everyone is only what he can replace everyone else with: fungible, a specimen. He himself, as an individual, is the absolutely replaceable, the pure nothing.\" The individual is of central importance for Adorno's theory in general."
