      "id": "d0a203dd2c501a82",
      "item": {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "id": "d0a203dd2c501a82",
        "text": "If one then looks at the posthumously published monograph The Politics of Society (PolG 2000), one might be inclined to say: old wine in new bottles - admittedly with the subtle difference that the wine has become much more mature in the meantime. Luhmann, for example, remained true to himself in no longer attaching the concept of politics to the traditional sense of Aristotelian terminology, because Aristotle's political society is no longer our society. One also encounters the same sequence of differentiation, autonomy, and functional specification with which Luhmann had approached the political system since 1968. Even the differentiation of the political system qua offices, i.e., via role differentiation, reappears, and even in determining the autonomy of the political system, Luhmann again addresses the function of the political system to produce collectively binding decisions. There is no doubt that Luhmann's political sociology shows certain constants over all these years."
